---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead
			title="About - AI Life OS"
			description="How AI Life OS works: an autonomous content pipeline that reads a production system, generates posts, reviews for privacy, and publishes."
		/>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<div class="page-wrap">
			<div class="prose">
				<h1>About this project</h1>
				<p>
					AI Life OS is a knowledge base documenting patterns for building AI-powered personal
					operating systems. Every post describes a real pattern, tool, or workflow pulled from
					a production system that manages projects, automates routine work, and continuously
					improves itself.
				</p>

				<h2>The system it documents</h2>
				<p>
					The source system is a personal operating system built on Obsidian, Claude Code, and a
					network of integrations. It uses file-based memory that persists across conversations,
					hook systems that enforce safety rules at the tool level, scheduled automations for
					recurring work, and a self-healing monitoring layer that watches infrastructure and
					escalates problems it cannot solve.
				</p>
				<p>
					The system is designed for people juggling work, school, family, and side projects
					who cannot afford to re-explain context every session. Every design decision
					optimizes for low friction, high reliability, and knowledge that compounds
					rather than resets.
				</p>

				<h2>Context that compounds</h2>
				<p>
					Most AI assistants forget everything between sessions. You re-explain context that
					was established hours ago. A memory architecture fixes this: typed memories stored
					as individual files, indexed by a lightweight manifest that loads at session start.
					Session 50 is qualitatively different from session 1 because the assistant knows your
					preferences, remembers past decisions, and builds on prior work.
				</p>
				<p>
					But compounding has a failure mode: corrections accumulate. Every "don't do X"
					rule makes the system safer in one context and more cautious everywhere. Without
					active grooming, a correction-based system drifts toward paralysis. A memory
					hygiene framework fixes this: corrections graduate to broader rules when universal,
					merge when redundant, and retire when stale. The count should trend down over time.
				</p>

				<h2>How the content pipeline works</h2>
				<p>
					This site generates its own content through an autonomous pipeline:
				</p>
				<ol>
					<li>An AI agent reads the source system: CLAUDE.md files, memory architecture, hook definitions, skill libraries, automation configs</li>
					<li>The agent identifies patterns worth documenting and drafts posts that explain the architecture and reasoning</li>
					<li>A privacy review strips personal details, names, financial data, and anything that should not be public</li>
					<li>Approved posts are committed and deployed via GitHub Actions to GitHub Pages</li>
				</ol>
				<p>
					Every post is reviewed before publishing. The agent proposes, a human approves.
					Over time, as the privacy layer proves reliable, the loop tightens toward full autonomy.
				</p>

				<h2>Autonomy with guardrails</h2>
				<p>
					A useful AI assistant acts on your behalf, not just when you tell it to. The system
					uses a three-tier autonomy framework: act without asking for internal operations,
					confirm before external-facing actions, and hard-stop on safety-critical prohibitions.
					An autonomy log tracks what the assistant decided on its own each session, and
					corrections feed back into the framework so the boundaries stay calibrated.
				</p>

				<h2>What you will find here</h2>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>System architecture:</strong> how memory, hooks, skills, and schedulers wire together</li>
					<li><strong>Practical patterns:</strong> solutions to real problems in AI-assisted workflows</li>
					<li><strong>Autonomy and trust:</strong> calibrating when the assistant acts, confirms, or refuses</li>
					<li><strong>Maintenance patterns:</strong> memory hygiene, caution accumulation, behavioral drift detection</li>
					<li><strong>Design principles:</strong> building for executive function, low friction, and continuous improvement</li>
					<li><strong>Honest assessments:</strong> what works, what breaks, and what the tradeoffs are</li>
				</ul>

				<h2>Built in the open</h2>
				<p>
					The source code, content pipeline, and deployment infrastructure are all on
					<a href="https://github.com/heathensxyz/ai-life-os" target="_blank">GitHub</a>.
					Fork it, adapt it, or just read the patterns.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
